<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="480" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[826,1441,1317,1553]" pageId="7" pageNumber="480">
<emphasis box="[826,1041,1317,1339]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="480">Generic diagnosis:</emphasis>
Male wings uniformly dark blue opaque or reddish brown with a distinctive area of the wing base, of variable size, which appears milky when viewed from an oblique angle, owing to the presence of bluish white cross-veins. The reticulation of the wings is dense to very dense, especially in the hind wings (
<figureCitation box="[834,956,1501,1523]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="7.[164,241,1036,1055]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1007]" captionTargetId="figure-313@7.[323,1283,195,1007]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 6. Right wings of males of Matrona species: A, M. basilaris (Qingliangfeng, Zhejiang); B, M. mazu sp. nov. (Baisha, Hainan; paratype, HaNBS02); C, M. oreades (Emeishan, Sichuan); D, M. taoi (Xuan Son, Vietnam; paratype)." pageId="7" pageNumber="480">Fig. 6A, B</figureCitation>
). Median space usually with 5–7 reticulated cross-veins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
